content:
To sort data in a dashboard widget, edit the dashboard widget. To set the first-level sorting behavior, choose an eligible group or measure from the Sort By dropdown. Click the arrow icon to change the sort direction between ascending and descending.

If you're working with a new widget, click Add. If you're working with an existing widget, click Update. To save the dashboard, click Save.

The table sorts data as you specified.

To apply two-level sorting in a dashboard, the source report must have groupings. Two-level sorting isn't available in Salesforce Classic. When you view a dashboard with two-level sorting in Salesforce Classic, components with two-level sorting sort by label ascending.

You can sort only by groups and measures that are visible in the dashboard widget. In a chart legend, text and fiscal date fields are sorted alphabetically. Numeric fields are sorted in ascending order. Picklist values are sorted in the order defined for the picklist.

Two-level sorting is available only for dashboard widgets that can show two groups or measures: Bar charts, Line charts, Scatter charts, Tables. You can sort by summary formulas, but keep these considerations in mind.

For example, say that there are two summary formulas in a dashboard widget’s source report. One is applied to Stage and one is applied to Type. The dashboard widget is grouped first by Stage and then by Type. The first level sorting can use the summary formula that applies to Stage but not the summary formula that applies to Type.

If you apply two-level sorting, review these notes and limitations:

* Source report must have groupings.
* Two-level sorting isn’t available in Salesforce Classic.
* You can sort only by groups and measures that are visible in the dashboard widget.
title: Sorting Data in Dashboard Widgets
